conclusions.conclusion:
For all $p,q\ge1$ the natural graded maps from augmentation-graded pieces to the stable page of the spectral sequence for $\overline{\operatorname{Hom}}(B(A),A^\vee)$ intertwine the commutator bracket on the augmentation quotients and the bracket induced on the spectral sequence. Explicitly, the square
$$
\begin{CD}
\tilde{J}^p/\tilde{J}^{p+1}\otimes\tilde{J}^q/\tilde{J}^{q+1} @>>> \overline{E}_\infty^{p,-p}\otimes\overline{E}_\infty^{q,-q} \\
@V[\ ,\ ]VV @VV[\ ,\ ]V \\
\tilde{J}^{p+q-2}/\tilde{J}^{p+q-1} @>>> \overline{E}_\infty^{p+q-2,-p-q+2}
\end{CD}
$$
commutes, where the right vertical bracket is the one induced from the Connes/cup/P construction on the spectral sequence $E$-pages and the horizontal maps are the identifications obtained via iterated integrals and the spectral-sequence comparison. This establishes that the filtration-graded bracket on $\mathbb{R}\tilde{\pi}$ corresponds, on associated graded pieces, to the bracket constructed on the Hom-complex spectral sequence.

  To prove that the algebraic bracket on the Hom-complex genuinely models the Goldman bracket one must check compatibility at the level of associated graded pieces for the augmentation filtration: the geometric commutator of representative loops with given augmentation degrees must be detected by the corresponding operations on iterated integrals and by the spectral sequence classes. Absent this commutativity there would be no rigorous identification between the filtration-graded Goldman bracket and the Hom-complex bracket. Proposition 6.4 supplies this precise comparison on $E_\infty$-graded pieces, based on explicit iterated-integral identities and the behavior of Thom and Connes operations.
